fc14@sol.acs.unt.edu (Tate Stephen Ralph) once said:

FC> Shirley And Ken Bass (bassanco@access.digex.net) wrote:
FC> 
FC> >  Assuming honesty in discovery (an 
FC> >  essential, but not always true, assumption) the alleged signer's secret 
FC> >  key could be used to test the validity of the signature by using it to 
FC> >  encrypt a new file in a monitored test that would prove to normal 
FC> >  evidentiary standards, that the signature that appeared on the challenged
FC> >  document was necessarily generated by the secret key of the alleged 
FC> >  signer.
FC> 
FC> I think you're missing the main point of signatures based on public key
FC> cryptography.  You don't need the private key (thus you don't need to
FC> trust in "honesty in discovery") to verify a signature, only the public key.
FC> 
FC> A signature scheme that would require turning over the secret key for every
FC> verification would be pretty useless....
FC> 
FC> 


